# AI Guardrails

**Ground truth**: Do not invent APIs, modules, paths, or files. If something is not in repo context or docs, say so and **ask** for the missing interface, contract, or file path instead of guessing.

**Behavior**: Preserve existing behavior unless the user explicitly asks to redesign or change semantics. Do not refactor or "clean up" unrelated code while doing a targeted task.

**Edits**: Prefer **minimal diffs**—touch only what the request requires. Avoid drive-by renames, formatting sweeps, or broad rewrites.

**Uncertainty**: When inference is required, **state assumptions and uncertainty explicitly** ("I don't know X; assuming Y unless you correct me").

**Safety**: Do not silently remove or weaken **validation**, **error handling**, **tests**, or **assertions**. If something must be removed or changed, call it out in the response and keep the change intentional and reviewable.

**Code authorship**: When writing or materially editing code, **logging, comments, and error handling are mandatory** — do not ship logic-only diffs.
- **Logging**: Follow `observability.mdc` and read **add-logging-to-code** when adding or editing log statements.
- **Comments**: Read **add-comments-to-code** when writing code. Explain **why**, not what. Document invariants, non-obvious constraints, complex branches, regex/math, and business rules. Skip comments only on trivial one-liners (imports, simple getters).
- **Error handling**: Follow scoped language rules (python-backend.mdc, go-backend.mdc) and read **add-error-handling-to-code** when adding or editing raise/except paths, domain error types, or failure translation at boundaries.

**Subagents when mentioned**: When the user names a subagent via `@agent(NAME)`, a path to `templates/agents/subagents/*.md` or `.cursor/agents/*.md`, or `agents_requested` in the resource ledger lists invoke names, **spawn** each subagent with the **Task** tool (`subagent_type` = that invoke name, e.g. `DOCS`, `BACKEND_PYTHON`) and delegate the relevant work. Do **not** substitute reading the agent `.md` in the parent agent. Spawn all mentioned agents; run in parallel when their tasks are independent. Before your final reply, every `agents_requested` entry must have a matching spawned subagent recorded in the ledger.

**Skills when task matches**: When `skills_matched` in the resource ledger lists skills, or the user asks for code review, cleanup, duplication/dead code, security review, or architecture fit, **read** each applicable `SKILL.md` with the Read tool before doing the work (do not substitute agent `.md` files for skills). Typical pairs: `audit-codebase-cleanup` + `review-pull-request` for repo cleanup/review; `security-scan-changes` for vuln/security checks; `review-architecture-fit` for module boundaries/ADRs. Subagents and skills complement each other — use both when the prompt requests agents **and** the task matches workflow skills.

**Customer-facing bot / AI runtime code** (paths: `**/bots/**`, `**/ai-runtime/**`, `**/ai-gateway/**`):
- Define a **human handoff path** before shipping; never silent dead-ends for end users.
- **No silent destructive tool execution** — write/destructive tools require policy `ask` or `deny` at runtime (mirror `validate-mcp-operations` semantics).
- **Ground truth for tool responses** — do not invent tool results; surface errors to operators, generic messages to customers.
- Read `orchestrate-ai-bot-delivery` or `design-customer-facing-agent` when building multi-step bot platforms.
